Use `sp.SkeletonAnimation` constructor or the static factory method `createWithJsonFile`. Both accept the skeleton JSON path, atlas path, and an optional scale.

```typescript
// Using constructor
const skel = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas', 1.0);
skel.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(skel);

// Using static factory
const skel2 = sp.SkeletonAnimation.createWithJsonFile('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas', 1.0);
skel2.setPosition(400, 160);
this.addChild(skel2);
```

The third parameter (scale) defaults to 1.0 and controls the skeleton's display scale. `sp.SkeletonAnimation` extends `sp.Skeleton` which extends `cc.Node`, so all node methods like `setPosition`, `setScale`, etc. are available.

Both are factory methods on `sp.SkeletonAnimation` that create a skeleton animation node, but they differ in the input format:

```typescript
// JSON-based skeleton data (human-readable, larger file)
const skelJson = sp.SkeletonAnimation.createWithJsonFile(
    'res/hero/hero.json',
    'res/hero/hero.atlas',
    1.0
);

// Binary skeleton data (compact, faster to parse)
const skelBin = sp.SkeletonAnimation.createWithBinaryFile(
    'res/hero/hero.skel',
    'res/hero/hero.atlas',
    1.0
);
```

JSON files (`.json`) are exported from Spine editor and are human-readable, useful during development. Binary files (`.skel`) are a compact binary export that loads faster and uses less memory â€” preferred for production builds. Both require the same `.atlas` file for texture regions. The resulting `sp.SkeletonAnimation` object works identically regardless of which method you use.

Use `setAnimation` on the `sp.SkeletonAnimation` instance. Pass track index 0 for the base animation, the animation name as exported from Spine, and `true` for looping:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

// Play 'run' animation looping on track 0
hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);
```

`setAnimation` returns a `spine.TrackEntry` or `null`. Track index 0 is the base layer â€” you can use higher indices for overlays (e.g., facial animations on track 1).

The `trackIndex` parameter specifies which animation track (slot) to play on. Tracks are layered â€” track 0 is the base, and higher tracks overlay on top. This lets you blend independent animations simultaneously.

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

// Track 0: body movement (run, idle, jump)
hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);

// Track 1: facial overlay (blink, smile) â€” plays on top of track 0
hero.setAnimation(1, 'blink', true);

// Track 2: weapon overlay
hero.setAnimation(2, 'sword_swing', false);
```

Each track is independent â€” clearing or changing track 0 does not affect track 1. Higher-numbered tracks override bone transforms from lower tracks where they overlap. Use `clearTrack(trackIndex)` to stop a specific track or `clearTracks()` to stop all.

Use `addAnimation` to queue animations after the current one on a given track. The `delay` parameter controls how many seconds to wait before the queued animation begins.

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

// Play jump once, then return to run loop
hero.setAnimation(0, 'jump', false);
hero.addAnimation(0, 'run', true, 0); // delay=0: start run immediately after jump ends

// More complex sequence: idle -> walk -> run
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', false);
hero.addAnimation(0, 'walk', false, 0);
hero.addAnimation(0, 'run', true, 0);
```

`addAnimation` returns a `spine.TrackEntry` for the queued entry. The `delay` is in seconds â€” use 0 to start right when the previous animation finishes, or a positive value to add a gap.

Use `clearTrack` to stop a specific track, or `clearTracks` to stop all tracks at once:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);
hero.setAnimation(1, 'blink', true);

// Stop only the body animation on track 0
hero.clearTrack(0);

// Stop ALL tracks (body, face, etc.)
hero.clearTracks();
```

`clearTrack(trackIndex)` stops and clears only the specified track. `clearTracks()` stops every active track. After clearing, the skeleton holds its last pose â€” call `setToSetupPose()` if you want to reset to the original bind pose.

Use `setAnimationListener` to register a callback that receives track entry, event type, and optional event data:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'attack', false);

hero.setAnimationListener(this, (track: spine.TrackEntry, type: number, event: spine.Event) => {
    if (type === sp.AnimationEventType.COMPLETE) {
        cc.log('Animation complete: ' + track.animation.name);
        // Return to idle after attack finishes
        hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);
    }
});
```

The `type` parameter matches `sp.AnimationEventType` constants: `START`, `END`, `COMPLETE`, and `EVENT`. `COMPLETE` fires each time a loop iteration finishes (for looping anims it fires every cycle). `END` fires when the animation is interrupted or cleared.

Custom events defined in the Spine editor are delivered through the animation listener with type `sp.AnimationEventType.EVENT`. The `event` parameter contains the event data:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);

hero.setAnimationListener(this, (track: spine.TrackEntry, type: number, event: spine.Event) => {
    if (type === sp.AnimationEventType.EVENT) {
        const eventName = event.data.name;
        cc.log('Frame event: ' + eventName);

        if (eventName === 'footstep') {
            cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/sfx_step.mp3');
        } else if (eventName === 'attack_hit') {
            this.applyDamageToEnemy();
        }
    }
});
```

`event.data.name` gives the event name as defined in Spine editor. You can also attach int, float, and string data to events in Spine â€” access them via `event.intValue`, `event.floatValue`, `event.stringValue`.

Use `setMix` to define crossfade durations between specific animation pairs:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

// Define blend transitions (must call before playing)
hero.setMix('idle', 'walk', 0.2);   // 0.2s blend from idle to walk
hero.setMix('walk', 'run', 0.3);    // 0.3s blend from walk to run
hero.setMix('run', 'idle', 0.2);    // 0.2s blend from run to idle
hero.setMix('walk', 'idle', 0.2);

// Now transitions will crossfade smoothly
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

// Later, when player starts moving:
hero.setAnimation(0, 'walk', true);  // blends over 0.2s

// Speed up:
hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);   // blends over 0.3s
```

`setMix(from, to, duration)` is directional â€” 'walk'->'run' does not automatically define 'run'->'walk'. You need to set both directions explicitly if you want smooth transitions both ways.

Use the `setSkin` method from `sp.Skeleton` (the base class of `sp.SkeletonAnimation`):

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

// Switch to warrior skin
hero.setSkin('warrior');

// Switch to mage skin
hero.setSkin('mage');

// After switching skin, reset to setup pose to apply new attachments
hero.setSlotsToSetupPose();
```

Skin names must match those defined in the Spine editor project. After switching skins, call `setSlotsToSetupPose()` to ensure all slots pick up the new skin's default attachments. The current animation continues playing with the new skin.

Use `setAttachment(slotName, attachmentName)` to show a specific attachment in a slot, or pass `null` to hide it:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

// Show sword in weapon slot
hero.setAttachment('weapon_slot', 'sword');

// Switch to axe
hero.setAttachment('weapon_slot', 'axe');

// Hide weapon entirely
hero.setAttachment('weapon_slot', null);
```

Slot names and attachment names must match exactly as defined in the Spine editor. This is useful for equipping/unequipping items without changing the entire skin.

You can control speed at two levels â€” globally on the skeleton, or per-track on the `TrackEntry`:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

// Global time scale â€” affects ALL tracks
hero.setTimeScale(0.5);  // half speed (slow motion)
hero.setTimeScale(1.0);  // normal speed
hero.setTimeScale(2.0);  // double speed

const currentScale = hero.getTimeScale();

// Per-track speed via TrackEntry
const track = hero.setAnimation(0, 'attack', false);
if (track) {
    track.timeScale = 2.0;  // only this track plays at 2x
}
```

`setTimeScale` on the skeleton multiplies with the per-track `timeScale`. So if skeleton timeScale is 0.5 and track timeScale is 2.0, the effective speed is 1.0.

Use `findBone` to get a `spine.Bone` reference, then read its position:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

// Find the bone
const headBone = hero.findBone('head');
if (headBone) {
    // Bone position is in skeleton-local space
    const localX = headBone.worldX;
    const localY = headBone.worldY;

    // Convert to world position by adding skeleton's position
    const worldX = hero.getPositionX() + localX;
    const worldY = hero.getPositionY() + localY;
    cc.log('Head world position: ' + worldX + ', ' + worldY);
}
```

`findBone` returns `spine.Bone | null`. The bone's `worldX`/`worldY` are in the skeleton's local coordinate space. Call `updateWorldTransform()` first if you need up-to-date bone positions before the next render.

Use `getBoundingBox()` which returns a `cc.Rect` encompassing the skeleton:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

// Get bounding box
const bbox = hero.getBoundingBox();
cc.log('Bounds: x=' + bbox.x + ' y=' + bbox.y + ' w=' + bbox.width + ' h=' + bbox.height);

// Use for simple collision detection
const enemyBox = enemy.getBoundingBox();
if (cc.rectIntersectsRect(bbox, enemyBox)) {
    cc.log('Collision detected!');
}
```

`getBoundingBox()` returns a `cc.Rect` in the parent node's coordinate space. Note that this is an axis-aligned bounding box and may not perfectly match the visual shape of the skeleton, especially during animations. For more precise collision, use Spine's bounding box attachments.

Use `setDebugBonesEnabled` and `setDebugSlotsEnabled` to toggle visual debug overlays:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

// Show debug bone lines
hero.setDebugBonesEnabled(true);

// Show debug slot bounding boxes
hero.setDebugSlotsEnabled(true);

// Disable when done
hero.setDebugBonesEnabled(false);
hero.setDebugSlotsEnabled(false);
```

Debug bones draws lines between bone positions, making the skeleton structure visible. Debug slots draws colored rectangles around slot attachment areas. These are useful during development to verify bone positions and slot placements â€” disable them in production builds.

Use one of the three reset methods on `sp.Skeleton`:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

// After playing animations, reset everything
hero.setToSetupPose();      // resets both bones AND slots to setup pose

// Or reset selectively:
hero.setBonesToSetupPose();  // reset only bone transforms (positions, rotations)
hero.setSlotsToSetupPose();  // reset only slot attachments and colors
```

`setToSetupPose()` is equivalent to calling both `setBonesToSetupPose()` and `setSlotsToSetupPose()`. Use `setSlotsToSetupPose()` after switching skins to apply the new skin's default attachments. Use `setBonesToSetupPose()` to undo any programmatic bone manipulation.

`setAnimation` and `addAnimation` return a `spine.TrackEntry` (or `null`) that provides control over a specific track's playback:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setPosition(240, 160);
this.addChild(hero);

const track = hero.setAnimation(0, 'attack', false);
if (track) {
    // Read-only info
    cc.log('Playing: ' + track.animation.name);  // spine.Animation reference
    cc.log('Loop: ' + track.loop);
    cc.log('Current time: ' + track.trackTime);
    cc.log('Duration: ' + track.trackEnd);
    cc.log('Anim time: ' + track.getAnimationTime());

    // Writable properties
    track.timeScale = 1.5;       // per-track speed multiplier
    track.alpha = 0.8;           // blend weight 0â€“1
    track.loop = true;           // change looping at runtime
    track.delay = 0.5;           // delay before starting
    track.mixDuration = 0.3;     // crossfade duration into this animation
}
```

`alpha` controls how strongly this track's animation applies â€” useful for partial blending on overlay tracks.

```typescript
class HeroLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private hero: sp.SkeletonAnimation;

    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        this.hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
        this.hero.setPosition(240, 160);
        this.addChild(this.hero);

        // Setup blending
        this.hero.setMix('idle', 'attack', 0.1);
        this.hero.setMix('attack', 'idle', 0.2);

        // Start idle
        this.hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

        // Listen for animation completion
        this.hero.setAnimationListener(this, this.onAnimationEvent.bind(this));

        // Enable touch
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            onTouchBegan: () => {
                this.onAttack();
                return true;
            }
        }, this);

        return true;
    }

    private onAttack(): void {
        this.hero.setAnimation(0, 'attack', false);
        this.hero.addAnimation(0, 'idle', true, 0);
    }

    private onAnimationEvent(
        track: spine.TrackEntry, type: number, event: spine.Event
    ): void {
        if (type === sp.AnimationEventType.EVENT && event.data.name === 'attack_hit') {
            cc.log('Deal damage!');
        }
    }
}

const scene = new cc.Scene();
scene.addChild(new HeroLayer());
cc.director.runScene(scene);
```

This creates a hero that idles by default, plays attack on tap, then auto-returns to idle via `addAnimation`. The `setMix` calls ensure smooth crossfades between states. The animation listener detects custom Spine events like 'attack_hit' for gameplay logic.

```typescript
class CharacterSelectLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private hero: sp.SkeletonAnimation;
    private skins: string[] = ['warrior', 'mage', 'archer', 'rogue'];
    private currentSkinIndex: number = 0;
    private nameLabel: cc.LabelTTF;

    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();

        this.hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
        this.hero.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2 - 40);
        this.addChild(this.hero);

        // Setup blending for all preview animations
        this.hero.setMix('idle', 'run', 0.2);
        this.hero.setMix('run', 'attack', 0.15);
        this.hero.setMix('attack', 'idle', 0.2);

        this.applySkin();
        this.hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);

        this.nameLabel = new cc.LabelTTF(this.skins[0], 'Arial', 24);
        this.nameLabel.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height - 60);
        this.addChild(this.nameLabel);

        // Swipe to change skin
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch) => {
                this.onTouchStart(touch);
                return true;
            }
        }, this);

        return true;
    }

    private onTouchStart(touch: cc.Touch): void {
        const loc = touch.getLocation();
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();

        if (loc.x > winSize.width / 2) {
            this.currentSkinIndex = (this.currentSkinIndex + 1) % this.skins.length;
        } else {
            this.currentSkinIndex = (this.currentSkinIndex - 1 + this.skins.length) % this.skins.length;
        }

        this.applySkin();
        this.previewAnimations();
    }

    private applySkin(): void {
        const skinName = this.skins[this.currentSkinIndex];
        this.hero.setSkin(skinName);
        this.hero.setSlotsToSetupPose();
        if (this.nameLabel) {
            this.nameLabel.setString(skinName.toUpperCase());
        }
    }

    private previewAnimations(): void {
        this.hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', false);
        this.hero.addAnimation(0, 'attack', false, 0);
        this.hero.addAnimation(0, 'idle', true, 0);
    }
}
```

Tap the right half to cycle forward through skins, left half to go back. Each skin change triggers a preview sequence (run -> attack -> idle). `setSlotsToSetupPose()` ensures the new skin's attachments are applied correctly.

